    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-12-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-12-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="646"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d646">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Choate</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-12-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 21, 1899</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 263.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose for your information copy of a
                        letter<note n="2" xml:id="d646fn2">(Inclosure:) Mr. R. M. Geldart to Mr.
                        Hay, December 15, 1899, printed ante.</note> from Mr. R. M. Geldart, of New
                    York City, who complains that certain merchandise belonging to him and shipped
                    to a Portuguese firm in Lourenço Marquez on board the British steamship <hi
                        rend="italic">Beatrice</hi>, was by order of the British Government
                    discharged into lighters at East London without Mr. Geldart’s consent.</p>
                <p>You are instructed to investigate the matter with a view to ascertaining the
                    facts, in order that the same may be reported to the Department for such action
                    as may be found proper.</p>
                <p>The United States consul at Lourenço Marquez will be instructed to use all proper
                    efforts to protect Mr. Geldart’s rights.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
